data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. Here's what's happening:

### The Problem

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions make `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this Span<T>, T)` a better overload match than `Enumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on arrays.

The compiler now binds `array.Contains(num)` to the `MemoryExtensions` overload. **Expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based calls**, so this throws at runtime (typically `NotSupportedException` or `InvalidOperationException`) when the expression is compiled.

### The Fix

Force the compiler to bind to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting or converting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three approaches prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the call representable in an expression tree.
